  "prompt": "If time slows down as you approach the speed of light, then what time scale is light on?",
  "response": "The concept you're referring to comes from Einstein's theory of relativity, specifically the idea of time dilation. As an object approaches the speed of light, time as experienced by that object (or in the frame of reference of that object) appears to slow down relative to a stationary observer. \n\nFor a massless particle like a photon, which travels at the speed of light, the situation is quite different. From the perspective of the photon itself (which is a conceptual perspective as photons do not have a rest frame), time does not progress at all. In other words, from the photon's \u201cpoint of view,\u201d the journey it takes occurs instantaneously, regardless of the distance it travels. \n\nIn more technical terms, as an object moves closer to the speed of light, the time experienced by that object approaches zero from the perspective of a stationary observer. Since photons travel at the speed of light, they effectively exist outside the normal framework of time as we understand it in relativity. Thus, from a light's \"perspective,\" there is no time taken for it to travel from point A to point B \u2013 the concept of elapsed time does not apply to photons.",
